<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41359648</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>24</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>15</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1530-6992</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>25</Volume><Issue>51</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Dec</Month><Day>24</Day></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Nano letters</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Nano Lett</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Near-Equilibrium Unbinding of Streptavidin-Biotin Using Single-Molecule Acoustic Force Spectroscopy.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>17547</StartPage><EndPage>17555</EndPage><MedlinePgn>17547-17555</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1021/acs.nanolett.5c03736</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>The dissociation of the streptavidin-biotin (SA-b) bond has been widely characterized using bulk and single-molecule force spectroscopy (SMFS) techniques. However, dissociation rates (<i>k</i><sub>off</sub>) from SMFS (&#x223c;10<sup>-1</sup> s<sup>-1</sup>) differ from bulk approaches (&#x223c;10<sup>-6</sup>-10<sup>-5</sup> s<sup>-1</sup>), likely because SMFS measurements are conducted far from equilibrium. Near-equilibrium SMFS requires high-throughput measurements to obtain large enough statistics and high stability over long periods for ultraslow loading force rates measurements, impractical in most SMFS techniques. Here, we developed <i>in situ</i> force calibration strategies for acoustic force spectroscopy to probe SA-b unbinding forces in the near-equilibrium regime, from 10 down to 10<sup>-3</sup> pN/s. The resulting <i>k</i><sub>off</sub> matches bulk measurements values. Combined with our previous data, we covered 15 orders of magnitude in loading rate, expanding the dynamic range of SMFS and enabling a more complete description of the energy landscape of biomolecular processes.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Saravanan</LastName><ForeName>Yogesh</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0009-0004-8690-818X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Aix-Marseille Univ, INSERM, DyNaMo, Turing Centre for Living Systems, Marseille 13009, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Villanueva</LastName><ForeName>Lorenzo</ForeName><Initials>L</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-0158-9980</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Aix-Marseille Univ, INSERM, DyNaMo, Turing Centre for Living Systems, Marseille 13009, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Leveque</LastName><ForeName>Christian</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0003-2583-2148</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Aix-Marseille Univ, INSERM, DyNaMo, Turing Centre for Living Systems, Marseille 13009, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Modesti</LastName><ForeName>Mauro</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-4964-331X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Aix-Marseille Univ, CNRS, INSERM, Cancer Research Center of Marseille, Department of Genome Integrity, Institut Paoli-Calmettes, Turing Centre for Living Systems, Marseille 13009, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>El Far</LastName><ForeName>Oussama</ForeName><Initials>O</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-7473-8345</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Aix-Marseille Univ, INSERM, DyNaMo, Turing Centre for Living Systems, Marseille 13009, France.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Valotteau</LastName><ForeName>Claire</ForeName><Initials>C</Initials><Identifier Source="ORCID">0000-0002-1436-8506</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation